arch:property.oc:show_val: This is a fill locus in the western half of the trench extension. It is bordered on the east by a pit L176. L177, a third millenium pit next to the southern baulk, was cut into it. This pit turned into a brick-lined pit in a mudbrick structure that took up mmost of this area. The locus was cut with a big pick to go down most of the centimeters, and there were no significant finds other than this mudbrick structure, L189. A series of grain lenses were found in the northeastern corner of the trench which were originally thought to be surfaces. There were at least three, and now we think its simply where grain was once on a lower surface. This locus was divided arbitrarily from L178 in order to break up the area, but these are the same. 585.95
small rock inclusions and some mudbrick debris

arch:note.arch:string: Contexts excavated in trenches were recorded using the "locus system." A locus is any discrete three-dimensional entity excavated in a trench. The key to the locus system is the recognition that a locus is any one thing. Differences in soil composition or texture are therefore as important as, for example, the difference between a pit and a wall. If two entities were distinct, they were considered separate loci and were therefore assigned separate locus numbers. It should also be noted that every context excavated in a trench was given a locus number and thus the trench itself is made up completely of excavated loci.
